# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: progressive-delivery-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Multivariate testing or multinomial testing is similar to A/B testing but may test more than two versions at the same time or use more controls.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Simple A/B tests are not valid for observational, quasi-experimental or other non-experimental situations—commonplace with survey data, offline data, and other, more complex phenomena.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] "A/B testing" is a shorthand for a simple randomized controlled experiment, in which a number of samples (e.g.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A and B) of a single vector-variable are compared.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests are widely considered the simplest form of controlled experiment, especially when they only involve two variants.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] However, by adding more variants to the test, its complexity grows.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A company has a customer database of 2,000 people and launches an email campaign with a discount code in order to generate sales through its website.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The company creates two versions of the email with different calls to action (the part of the copy that encourages customers to act—in the case of a sales campaign, make a purchase) and identifying promotional codes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The company then monitors which campaign has the higher success rate by analyzing the use of the promotional codes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The email using the code A1 has a 5% response rate (50 of the 1,000 people emailed used the code to buy a product), and the email using the code B1 has a 3% response rate (30 of the recipients used the code to buy a product).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The company therefore determines that in this instance, the first call to action is more effective and will use it in future sales.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A more nuanced approach would involve applying statistical testing to determine whether the differences in response rates between A1 and B1 were statistically significant (highly likely that the differences are real, repeatable and not the result of random chance).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In the previous example, the purpose of the test is to determine the more effective strategy to encourage customers to make a purchase.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] If, however, the aim of the test had been to determine which email would generate the higher clickthrough rate (the percentage of people who actually click the link after receiving the email), the results might have been different.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] For example, even though more of the customers receiving the code B1 accessed the website, because the call to action did not state the end date of the promotion, many recipients may feel no urgency to make an immediate purchase.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Consequently, if the purpose of the test had been simply to determine which email would bring more traffic to the website, the email containing code B1 might well have been more successful.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] An A/B test should have a defined, measurable outcome, such as sales converted, clickthrough rate or registration rate.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Two-sample hypothesis tests are appropriate for comparing the two samples in which the samples are divided by the two control cases in the experiment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Z-tests are appropriate for comparing means under stringent conditions regarding normality and a known standard deviation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Student's *t*-tests are appropriate for comparing means under relaxed conditions when less is assumed.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Welch's *t*-test assumes the least and is therefore the most commonly used two-sample hypothesis test in which the mean of a metric is to be optimized.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] While the mean of the variable to be optimized is the most common choice of estimator, others are regularly used.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Fisher's exact test can be employed to compare two binomial distributions, such as a click-through rate.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests most commonly apply the same variant (e.g., user interface element) with equal probability to all users.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] However, in some circumstances, responses to variants may be heterogeneous.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] While a variant A might have a higher response rate overall, variant B may have an even higher response rate within a specific segment of the customer base.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In this case, while variant A attracted a higher response rate overall, variant B actually elicited a higher response rate with men.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] As a result, the company might select a segmented strategy as a result of the A/B test, sending variant B to men and variant A to women in the future.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] If segmented results are expected from the A/B test, the test should be properly designed at the outset to be evenly distributed across key customer attributes, such as gender.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The test should contain a representative sample of men vs. women and assign men and women randomly to each “variant” (variant A vs. variant B).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Failure to do so could lead to experiment bias and inaccurate conclusions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] This segmentation and targeting approach can be further generalized to include multiple customer attributes rather than a single customer attribute—for example, customers' age and gender—to identify more nuanced patterns that may exist in the test results.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The results of A/B tests are simple to interpret to create a clear picture of real user preferences, as they directly test one option over another.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests can also provide answers to highly specific design questions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] One example of this is Google's A/B testing with hyperlink colors.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In order to optimize revenue, Google tested dozens of hyperlink hues to determine which colors attract the most clicks.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests are sensitive to variance; they require a large sample size in order to reduce standard error and produce a statistically significant result.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In applications in which active users are abundant, such as with popular online social-media platforms, obtaining a large sample size is trivial.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In other cases, large sample sizes are obtained by increasing the experiment enrollment period.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] However, using a technique coined by Microsoft as Controlled Experiment Using Pre-Experiment Data (CUPED), variance from before the experiment start can be taken into account so that fewer samples are required to produce a statistically significant result.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Because of its nature as an experiment, running an A/B test introduces the risk of wasted time and resources if the test produces unwanted or unhelpful results.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In December 2018, representatives with experience in large-scale A/B testing from 13 organizations (Airbnb, Amazon, Booking.com, Facebook, Google, LinkedIn, Lyft, Microsoft, Netflix, Twitter, Uber and Stanford University) summarized the top challenges in a paper.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The challenges were grouped into four areas: analysis, engineering and culture, deviations from traditional A/B tests and data quality.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] It is difficult to definitively establish when A/B testing was first used.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The first randomized double-blind trial to assess the effectiveness of a homeopathic drug occurred in 1835.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Experimentation with advertising campaigns, which has been compared to modern A/B testing, began in the early 20th century.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The advertising pioneer Claude Hopkins used promotional coupons to test the effectiveness of his campaigns.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] However, this process, which Hopkins described in his 1923 book *Scientific Advertising*, did not incorporate concepts such as statistical significance and the null hypothesis, which are used in statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Modern statistical methods for assessing the significance of sample data were developed separately in the same period.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] This work was conducted in 1908 by William Sealy Gosset when he altered the Z-test to create Student's *t*-test.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] With the growth of the internet, new ways to sample populations have become available.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Google engineers ran their first A/B test in 2000 to determine the optimum number of results to display in its search-engine results.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] The first test was unsuccessful because of glitches that resulted from slow loading times.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Later A/B testing research was more advanced, but the foundation and underlying principles generally remain the same, and in 2011, Google ran more than 7,000 different A/B tests.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In 2012, a Microsoft employee working on the search engine Bing created an experiment to test different methods of displaying advertising headlines.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Within hours, the alternative format produced a revenue increase of 12% with no impact on user-experience metrics.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Today, major software companies such as Microsoft and Google each conduct over 10,000 A/B tests annually.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B testing has been claimed by some to be a change in philosophy and business-strategy in certain niches, although the approach is identical to a between-subjects design, which is commonly used in a variety of research traditions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B testing as a philosophy of web development brings the field into line with a broader movement toward evidence-based practice.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Many companies now use the "designed experiment" approach to making marketing decisions, with the expectation that relevant sample results can improve positive conversion results.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] It is an increasingly common practice as the tools and expertise grow in this area.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] As a result, more marketing teams now use A/B testing to guide decisions, matching the rigor of the test to measured hypotheses and measuring impact on outcomes such as conversions, revenue, and downstream conversion.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests have been used by large social-media sites such as LinkedIn, Facebook and Instagram to understand user engagement and satisfaction of online features, such as a new feature or product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests have also been used to conduct complex experiments on subjects such as network effects when users are offline, how online services affect user actions and how users influence one another.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] On an e-commerce website, the purchase funnel is typically a helpful candidate for A/B testing, as even marginal decreases in drop-off rates can represent a significant gain in sales.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Significant improvements can be sometimes seen through testing elements such as copy text, layouts, images and colors.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In these tests, users only see one of two versions, as the goal is to discover which of the two versions is preferable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B testing can be used to determine the right price for a product, which is one of the most difficult challenges faced when a new product or service is launched.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B testing (especially valid for digital goods) is an effective mechanism to identify the price point that maximizes the total revenue.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B tests have also been used by political campaigns.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] In 2007, Barack Obama's presidential campaign used A/B testing to garner online attraction and understand what voters wanted to see from Obama.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] For example, Obama's team tested four distinct buttons on their website that led users to register for newsletters.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] Additionally, the team used six different accompanying images to attract users.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] A/B testing is commonly employed when deploying a newer version of an API.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] For real-time user experience testing, an HTTP layer 7 reverse proxy is configured in such a way that *n*% of the HTTP traffic is routed to the newer version of the backend instance, while the remaining *100-n*% of HTTP traffic hits the (stable) older version of the backend HTTP application service.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/a-b-testing] This is usually achieved to limit the exposure of customers to a newer backend instance such that, if there is a bug with the newer version, only *n*% of the total user agents or clients are affected while others are routed to a stable backend, which is a common ingress control mechanism.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A **feature toggle** in software development provides an alternative to maintaining multiple feature branches in source code.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A condition within the code enables or disables a feature during runtime.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] In agile settings the toggle is used in production, to switch on the feature on demand, for some or all the users.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Thus, feature toggles do make it easier to release often.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Advanced roll out strategies such as canary roll out and A/B testing are easier to handle.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Continuous delivery is supported by feature toggles, even if new releases are not deployed to production continuously.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] The feature is integrated into the main branch even before it is completed.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] The version is deployed into a test environment once, the toggle allows to turn the feature on, and test it.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Software integration cycles get shorter, and a version ready to go to production can be provided.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] The third use of the technique is to allow developers to release a version of a product that has unfinished features.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] These unfinished features are hidden (toggled) so that they do not appear in the user interface.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] There is less effort to merge features into and out of the productive branch, and hence allows many small incremental versions of software.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A feature toggle is also called **feature switch**, **feature flag**, **feature gate**, **feature flipper**, or **conditional feature**.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Feature toggles are essentially variables that are used inside conditional statements.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Therefore, the blocks inside these conditional statements can be toggled 'on or off' depending on the value of the feature toggle.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] This allows developers to control the flow of their software and bypass features that are not ready for deployment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A block of code behind a runtime variable is usually still present and can be conditionally executed, sometimes within the same application lifecycle; a block of code behind a preprocessor directive or commented out would not be executable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A feature flag approach could use any of these methods to separate code paths in different phases of development.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] The main usage of feature toggles is to avoid conflict that can arise when merging changes in software at the last moment before release, although this can lead to toggle debt.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Toggle debt arises due to the dead code present in software after a feature has been toggled on permanently and produces overhead.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] This portion of the code has to be removed carefully as to not disturb other parts of the code.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Feature toggles usually require lifecycle management beyond the conditional statements used to implement them.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A study of practitioner material and developers from 38 companies identified 17 practices for feature-toggle use, grouped into management, initialization, implementation, and clean-up practices.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Commonly reported practices included recording metadata for each toggle, defining a default value, logging changes made to toggles, and using dedicated tools to manage them.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Research on Google Chrome found that feature toggles can support rapid releases, trunk-based development, and A/B testing, but also require additional maintenance when toggles remain in the codebase for long periods.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Later work on feature-toggle structure similarly noted that toggles may increase code complexity, introduce dead code, and reduce maintainability if they are not removed or organized after their purpose has ended.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] There are two main types of feature toggle.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] One is a release toggle, which the developer determines to either keep or remove before a product release depending on its working.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] The other is a business toggle, which is kept because it satisfies a different usage compared to that of the older code.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Feature groups consist of feature toggles that work together.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] This allows the developer to easily manage a set of related toggles.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] A **canary release** (or canary launch or canary deployment) allows developers to have features incrementally tested by a small set of users.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Feature flags are an alternate way to do canary launches and allow targeting by geographic locations or even user attributes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] If a feature's performance is not satisfactory, then it can be rolled back without any adverse effects.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] It is named after the use of canaries to warn miners of toxic gases.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Martin Fowler states that a release toggle, a specific type of feature toggle, "should be your last choice when you're dealing with putting features into production".
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Instead, it is best to break the feature into smaller parts that each can be implemented and safely introduced into the released product without causing other problems.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/feature-toggle] Feature-toggling is used by many large websites including Flickr, Disqus, Etsy, Reddit, Gmail and Netflix, as well as software such as Google Chrome Canary or Microsoft Office.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Reduce the risk of introducing a new software version in production by gradually shifting traffic to the new version while measuring metrics like HTTP/gRPC request success rate and latency.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Shift and route traffic between app versions automatically using an ingress controller or a service mesh compatible with Kubernetes Gateway API.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Besides the builtin metrics checks, you can extend your application analysis with custom metrics and webhooks for running acceptance tests, load tests, or any other custom validation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Flagger was designed to give developers confidence in automating production releases with progressive delivery techniques.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] A benefit of using canary releases is the ability to do capacity testing of the new version in a production environment with a safe rollback strategy if issues are found.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] By slowly ramping up the load, you can monitor and capture metrics about how the new version impacts the production environment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Flagger's application analysis can be extended with metric queries targeting Prometheus, Datadog, CloudWatch, New Relic, Graphite, Dynatrace, InfluxDB and Google Cloud Monitoring.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Flagger can be configured to send notifications (opens new window) to Slack, Microsoft Teams, Discord and Rocket.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] It will post messages when a deployment has been initialised, when a new revision has been detected and if the canary analysis failed or succeeded.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] You can build fully automated GitOps pipelines for canary deployments with Flagger and Flux (opens new window).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] GitOps is a way to do Kubernetes cluster management and application delivery.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] It works by using Git as a single source of truth for declarative infrastructure and applications.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] With Git at the center of your delivery pipelines, developers can make pull requests to accelerate and simplify application deployments and operations tasks to Kubernetes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Flagger is Apache 2.0 (opens new window) licensed and accepts contributions via GitHub pull requests.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] Flagger was initially developed in 2018 at Weaveworks by Stefan Prodan.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/flagger-app] In 2020 Flagger became a Cloud Native Computing Foundation (opens new window) project, part of Flux (opens new window) family of GitOps tools.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Argo Rollouts is a Kubernetes controller and set of CRDs which provide advanced deployment capabilities such as blue-green, canary, canary analysis, experimentation, and progressive delivery features to Kubernetes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Argo Rollouts (optionally) integrates with ingress controllers and service meshes, leveraging their traffic shaping abilities to gradually shift traffic to the new version during an update.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Additionally, Rollouts can query and interpret metrics from various providers to verify key KPIs and drive automated promotion or rollback during an update.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] The native Kubernetes Deployment Object supports the `RollingUpdate` strategy which provides a basic set of safety guarantees (readiness probes) during an update.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] For these reasons, in large scale high-volume production environments, a rolling update is often considered too risky of an update procedure since it provides no control over the blast radius, may rollout too aggressively, and provides no automated rollback upon failures.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Follow the full getting started guide to walk through creating and then updating a rollout object.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Similar to the deployment object, the Argo Rollouts controller will manage the creation, scaling, and deletion of ReplicaSets.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] These ReplicaSets are defined by the `spec.template` field inside the Rollout resource, which uses the same pod template as the deployment object.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] When the `spec.template` is changed, that signals to the Argo Rollouts controller that a new ReplicaSet will be introduced.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] The controller will use the strategy set within the `spec.strategy` field in order to determine how the rollout will progress from the old ReplicaSet to the new ReplicaSet.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] Once that new ReplicaSet is scaled up (and optionally passes an Analysis), the controller will mark it as "stable".
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/page] There is more information on the behaviors of each strategy in the spec section.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The **software release life cycle** is the process of developing, testing, and distributing a software product (e.g., an operating system).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] It typically consists of several stages, such as pre-alpha, alpha, beta, and release candidate, before the final version, or "gold", is released to the public.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to the early stages of development, when the software is still being designed and built.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha testing is the first phase of formal testing, during which the software is tested internally using white-box techniques.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Beta testing is the next phase, in which the software is tested by a larger group of users, typically outside the organization that developed it.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The beta phase is focused on reducing impacts on users and may include usability testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] After beta testing, the software may go through one or more release candidate phases, in which it is refined and tested further, before the final version is released.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Some software, particularly in the internet and technology industries, is released in a perpetual beta state, meaning that it is continuously being updated and improved, and is never considered to be a fully completed product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] This approach allows for a more agile development process and enables the software to be released and used by users earlier in the development cycle.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Pre-alpha refers to all activities performed during the software project before formal testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] These activities can include requirements analysis, software design, software development, and unit testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In typical open source development, there are several types of pre-alpha versions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] *Milestone* versions include specific sets of functions and are released as soon as the feature is complete.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase of the release life cycle is the first phase of software testing (alpha is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, used as the number 1).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In this phase, developers generally test the software using white-box techniques.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Additional validation is then performed using black-box or gray-box techniques, by another testing team.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Moving to black-box testing inside the organization is known as *alpha release*.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software is not thoroughly tested by the developer before it is released to customers.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may contain serious errors, and any resulting instability could cause crashes or data loss.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Alpha software may not contain all of the features that are planned for the final version.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In general, external availability of alpha software is uncommon for proprietary software, while open source software often has publicly available alpha versions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The alpha phase usually ends with a feature freeze, indicating that no more features will be added to the software.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] At this time, the software is said to be feature-complete.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A beta test is carried out following acceptance testing at the supplier's site (the alpha test) and immediately before the general release of the software as a product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A **feature-complete** (FC) version of a piece of software has all of its planned or primary features implemented but is not yet final due to bugs, performance or stability issues.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] This occurs at the end of alpha testing in development.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Usually, feature-complete software still has to undergo beta testing and bug fixing, as well as performance or stability enhancement before it can go to release candidate, and finally gold status.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Beta, named after the second letter of the Greek alphabet, is the software development phase following alpha.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A beta phase generally begins when the software is feature-complete but likely to contain several known or unknown bugs.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Software in the beta phase will generally have many more bugs in it than completed software and speed or performance issues, and may still cause crashes or data loss.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The focus of beta testing is reducing impacts on users, often incorporating usability testing.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The process of delivering a beta version to the users is called *beta release* and is typically the first time that the software is available outside the organization that developed it.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Software beta releases can be either open or closed, depending on whether they are openly available or only available to a limited audience.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Beta version software is often useful for demonstrations and previews within an organization and to prospective customers.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Some developers refer to this stage as a *preview*, *preview release*, *prototype*, *technical preview* or *technology preview* (*TP*).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is kept in so-called *perpetual beta*, where new features are continually added to the software without establishing a final "stable" release.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] As the Internet has facilitated the rapid and inexpensive distribution of software, companies have begun to take a looser approach to the use of the word *beta*.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A *release candidate* (*RC*), also known as gamma testing or "going silver", is a beta version with the potential to be a stable product, which is ready to release unless significant bugs emerge.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In this stage of product stabilization, all product features have been designed, coded, and tested through one or more beta cycles with no known showstopper-class bugs.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A release is called *code complete* when the development team agrees that no entirely new source code will be added to this release.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] There could still be source code changes to fix defects, changes to documentation and data files, and peripheral code for test cases or utilities.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Also called *production release*, the *stable release* is the last *release candidate* (*RC*) which has passed all stages of verification and tests.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Any known remaining bugs are considered acceptable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Linux distributions like Debian) also have *long-term support* (*LTS*) releases which are based on full releases that have already been tried and tested and receive only security updates.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Once released, the software is generally known as a "stable release".
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The formal term often depends on the method of release: physical media, online release, or a web application.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Usually the released software is assigned an official version name or version number.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] (Pre-release software may or may not have a separate internal project code name or internal version number).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The term "release to manufacturing" (RTM), also known as "going gold", is a term used when a software product is ready to be delivered.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] This build may be digitally signed, allowing the end user to verify the integrity and authenticity of the software purchase.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The RTM build is known as the "gold master" or GM is sent for mass duplication or disc replication if applicable.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The terminology is taken from the audio record-making industry, specifically the process of mastering.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] RTM precedes general availability (GA) when the product is released to the public.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] A golden master build (GM) is typically the final build of a piece of software in the beta stages for developers.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Typically, for iOS, it is the final build before a major release, however, there have been a few exceptions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] RTM could also mean in other contexts that the software has been delivered or released to a client or customer for installation or distribution to the related hardware end user computers or machines.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The term does *not* define the delivery mechanism or volume; it only states that the quality is sufficient for mass distribution.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The deliverable from the engineering organization is frequently in the form of a golden master media used for duplication or to produce the image for the web.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] During its supported lifetime, the software is sometimes subjected to service releases, patches or service packs, sometimes also called "interim releases" or "maintenance releases" (MR).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] For example, Microsoft released three major service packs for the 32-bit editions of Windows XP and two service packs for the 64-bit editions.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Such service releases contain a collection of updates, fixes, and enhancements, delivered in the form of a single installable package.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Some software is released with the expectation of regular support.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Classes of software that generally involve protracted support as the norm include anti-virus suites and massively multiplayer online games.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Continuing with this Windows XP example, Microsoft did offer paid updates for five more years after the end of extended support.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] This means that support ended on April 8, 2019.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] After the end-of-life date, the developer will usually not implement any new features, fix existing defects, bugs, or vulnerabilities (whether known before that date or not), or provide any support for the product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] If the developer wishes, they may release the source code, so that the platform may be maintained by volunteers.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Usage of the "alpha/beta" test terminology originated at IBM.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Similar terminologies for IBM's software development were used by people involved with IBM from at least the 1950s (and probably earlier).
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] "A" test was the verification of a new product before the public announcement.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The "B" test was the verification before releasing the product to be manufactured.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The "C" test was the final test before the general availability of the product.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] As software became a significant part of IBM's offerings, the alpha test terminology was used to denote the pre-announcement test and the beta test was used to show product readiness for general availability.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Martin Belsky, a manager on some of IBM's earlier software projects claimed to have invented the terminology.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] IBM dropped the alpha/beta terminology during the 1960s, but by then it had received fairly wide notice.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] The usage of "beta test" to refer to testing done by customers was not done in IBM.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Major public betas developed afterward, with early customers having purchased a "pioneer edition" of the WordVision word processor for the IBM PC for $49.95.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In 1984, Stephen Manes wrote that "in a brilliant marketing coup, Bruce and James Program Publishers managed to get people to *pay* for the privilege of testing the product." In September 2000, a *boxed version* of Apple's Mac OS X Public Beta operating system was released.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Between September 2005 and May 2006, Microsoft released *community technology preview*s (*CTP*s) for Windows Vista.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] From 2009 to 2011, *Minecraft* was in public beta.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] In February 2005, ZDNet published an article about the phenomenon of a beta version often staying for years and being used as if it were at the production level.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] It noted that Gmail and Google News, for example, had been in beta for a long time although widely used; Google News left beta in January 2006, followed by Google Apps (now named Google Workspace), including Gmail, in July 2009.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] Since the introduction of Windows 8, Microsoft has called pre-release software a *preview* rather than *beta*.
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] All pre-release builds released through the Windows Insider Program launched in 2014 are termed "Insider Preview builds".
[src:progressive-delivery-deep/software-release-life-cycle] "Beta" may also indicate something more like a release candidate, or as a form of time-limited demo, or marketing technique.
